name: Nick Ulivieri
bio:
I like my verticals parallel, skies wild, and hanging above Chicago. Shooting structures & architecture is my profession. ✶ ✶ ✶ ✶ 
📧: nick@nuphoto.com

social_posts.post_text: A hazy shade of winter // #Chitecture

When @goettschpartners' chairman and co-design director, James Goettsch, said, "It is our belief that how a building meets the ground is more important than how it meets the sky,” he wasn't kidding. @320southcanal fits this description to a T — or a V in this case.

Between the 1.5 acre park on the tower’s west side, and the dramatic V-shaped structural transfers that frame the lobby on the East side, there's no shortage of activation and interest for tenants and the general public.

That said, I'm excited to finally share some of the photos I created for Goettsch Partners and @riverside.chi this past summer. 

Check out GP's project summary linked in my bio to learn more about the tower.

#Chiarchitecture
✶ ✶Calder ✶ ✶

Before I dove into architecture photography full-time, I did a fair bit of photo work for food and hospitality brands, too.
But as @amyulo’s roster of clients has grown, I've found myself assisting with her food & lifestyle projects more and more. We make a good team — Amy assists on a lot my architecture shoots, too.

Late in November, we worked together on a project for her client, @lhchicago. For this year's holiday-themed tea, the client wanted to capture an activated tea set-up with guests enjoying the experience. So Amy arranged some influencers to sip tea and enjoy the various bites from the sweet and savory tower while I shot stills and Amy directed and captured video. 

Here are a few of my favorite frames
This raw, dreary weather is a mood, huh? I can’t remember the last sunny day here in Chicago. I think I’m ready to hibernate for the rest of 2022. Anyone else?
I don’t know if it’ll be cold enough for long enough to get a good freeze on the river, but we’re in for a bone-chillingly cold week. Bundle up! #ILwx

Welp, tomorrow's the day we'll see what the weather brings. Cold air is racing across the plains as we speak, but how much snow we get is yet to be determined - though frigid temps and high winds may create blizzard-like conditions even if "only" get few inches of snow. 

If you venture out into the snow tomorrow, try using your flash while the snow is falling to create #snokeh. It's a fun way to add layers and depth to winter photos.

Temps will drop fast midday Thursday, so layer-up and stuff some hand warmers in your gloves. Check out my linktree in my profile for a tutorial. #ILwx

The girl with the rainbow umbrella.

If you’re like me and need to get to the airport six hours before your flight, O'Hare's new United Club club offers an incredible vantage point to watch airport operations up close as you pass the time. Just before it opened last week, I had the opportunity to photograph the sprawling space for my friends at @power_construct.

Not only did they build-out the interior space, they also built the underlying superstructure - the first major addition to T1 since the 80s. Plus, how about that view of Gate C16? You can watch the wide-body jets roll in and out.
They don’t make ‘em like this anymore // #chiarchitecture

I photographed this juvenile Cooper's hawk perched in my neighbor's tree just this morning.

Ever since we put a bird feeder out on our 5th floor balcony after Christmas, we've had a few hawks and falcons "buzz the tower." A female kestrel was successful in snatching a sparrow from the feeder a couple weeks ago, and we've seen these bigger hawks swoop in a few times, too. 

This hawk landed in the same spot yesterday, but I didn't have my camera ready. Today, my telephoto was close by and ready to go just in case. Suddenly, the sparrows and finches at the feeder scrambled for their lives and we saw this hawk swoop in and land in the tree. I quickly grabbed my camera and slid into the kitchen and snagged this photo through the sliding door from about 10' away.

Now I need to find a way to get one of these raptors in front of the skyline. Looking forward to more of Mother Nature's Air Show...see what I did there?

@amyulo and I spent some *time* shooting content at @lhchicago last night. Here’s a peek at @thewrigleybuilding between the curtains.

This is a 111 S. Wacker appreciation post. I've been a fan of this tower since before I picked up a camera. It so fascinated me to learn the lobby's spiral ceiling isn't just an aesthetic detail but a structural necessity — It's the underside of the building's parking garage ramp! 

Completed in 2005, this 681' tower was designed by Goettsch Partners. Which isn't surprising since Jim Goettsch's - the firm's chairman - often says "how a building meets the ground is more important than how it meets the sky.”

I've never found myself around 111 at blue hour, so while walking to a nearby shoot, I quickly popped out my tripod and fired off a few frames of the lobby before continuing on my way. // #Chiarchitecture

I had a meeting along Michigan Avenue this morning, but I left the house a little early to take a few shots of @1000mchicago - one of Helmut Jahn’s final designs -  continuing its climb above Grant Park. Once complete, the 73-story skyscraper will stand 805' above Michigan Avenue.

By my count, approximately 45 levels have been poured so there are still nearly 30 floors left to go before this one tops out!

I wasn't sure how I'd like the transition between the asymmetrical angular podium, and the main body of the tower, but I'm digging it. I can't wait to revisit some of these angles in spring - and again once this tower is complete // #Chiarchitecture

Last week I posted some exterior structure photos of @1000mchicago climb to 805'. But this post is about the McHugh Concrete team pouring this tower one floor at a time. 

Last August I visited the jobsite to photograph a slab pour for their new website and related marketing collateral. McHugh Concrete was in the middle of developing their website and needed some updated action photos of their team doing what they do best - pouring and setting concrete. ‘Up top’ I was able to capture a few photos of them in action pouring the tallest concrete skyscraper currently under construction in Chicago. 

Finished project photos are always rewarding to take, but to me, this is where the magic happens. Being on-site, watching and documenting raw materials turn into a skyscraper is a sight to behold. Check out all the projects McHugh Concrete has added to the Chicago skyline (and others) over the years at mchuhughconcrete.com // #chiarchitecture

Today is #GreatLakesAwarenessDay. So here's a photo of Lake Michigan absolutely dwarfing the Harrison-Dever water intake crib under a perfectly cloud-brushed sky.

I try not to take Lake Michigan for granted. It, and the entire Great Lakes chain, is a fascinating, unique ecosystem. It's an extreme privilege to live so close to one of earth's natural wonders. It may seem normal, but don't let it be.

The Great Lakes as we know them today are only about ~3,000 years old; barely a blink on the geologic timescale. Three. Thousand. They won't be around forever, either. Geologic processes and human-caused catastrophes will conspire against them. 

I wish I had more to say, but this is just a reminder to enjoy them whenever, however you can...and take care of them. the Great Lakes are a precious resource

Are days like today a harbinger of things to come? In a summer already filled with dozens of days featuring smoke-veiled skies, today is decidedly the worst​. ​For much of today the skyline was blotted out by smoke plumes pouring down from wildfires in eastern Canada. Since early this afternoon today was technically a sunny day. Not one single cloud filled the sky. What you see - and smell - in the air isn’t fog or humidity-driven haze; it's all smoke - the charred, microscopic remnants of countless trees incinerated within Canada’s sprawling forests. 

​According to the ​Canadian Interagency Forest Fire Centre, “​this year's wildfire season is the worst on record in Canada, with some​ ​29,000 square miles burning across eastern and western Canada. That's greater than the combined area burned in 2016, 2019, 2020 and 2022.” This is not fine. Hopefully this year is an outlier, but I fear we’re trending in the wrong direction.

This photo isn’t desaturated. And aside from removing some sensor spots it’s barely edited. The skyline - only 1.25 miles away - is barely visible through the wildfire smoke. Nearer expressway lights help add the slightest bit of dimension to an otherwise flat image.

It’s a stark reminder of the things we'll need to contend with as climate change worsens. I’ve probably said it before, but days like today are visual alarms that, perhaps, signal the future dystopia we've feared might actually be here, now, at present. #ILwx #ChicagoWX

*the second photo is a mashup of an image from late last spring and one from today

Happy #4thofjuly, everyone! If you’re going to photograph fireworks tonight, give the focus pull technique a try - it’s a fun way to capture atypical images of fireworks. All of this is done in camera simply by twisting your lens’ focus ring *during* the exposure. Here are a few tips:

1) Use a wide aperture - the more you open up, the bigger your bokeh will be.

2) Zoom in: it’s tempting to shoot fireworks wide. But if you zoom into the heart of the firework (not always easy) it’ll pay off with a surreal display of color

3) I like to start out of focus, then twist into focus - different twisting speeds will yield different results. You can also do the opposite. The key is to experiment! Almost every exposure yields a different result! 

If it helps, use masking tape on your lens/focus ring to help locate ♾️ so it’s easier to (hopefully) get the image into focus

4) Be patient: Not every frame will yield a good shot. The firework might be too out of frame or you might never get into focus. It happens more often than not. Most frames are not very good. Keep trying. 

#photography #phototutorial #focuspull

I’m an Oppie boy in a Barbie world

On July 16, 1945 - 78 years ago today - the “gadget” was detonated at the trinity test site in the New Mexico desert. Under Robert Oppenheimer’s direction, the world entered the atomic age. 

I’ve had a fascination with all things atomic since junior high. I’ve watched documentaries and read books about the subject but can’t wait to see this story brought to life on @imax. Needless to say, I can’t wait to see @oppenheimermovie . 

This is a sunset photo taken from Porter Beach along the Indiana Dunes. When I was originally editing, I accidentally applied a b&w edit, and for a moment the sun - morbidly - reminded me of imagery taken milliseconds after an atomic bomb test detonations - well before the telltale mushroom cloud ascended into the sky

I ‘aged’ my photo by de-sharperning it, and adding a fair amount of grain. I aded the time stamp and scale to re-create the look of archival images…those of which, thankfully did not include the Chicago skyline. This is something I hope no one ever has to witness again

But when the sun rises after 7:00am at this time of year, I can justify it. Amy and I went out early on Saturday to catch some shots in Grant Park, but the clouds skunked us. Today was another weird Halloween! As I was working on this post I saw a few flashes of thundersnow (paging @jimcantore). Mother Nature has played some Halloween tricks on Chicago in recent years. On October 31st of 2014 and 2019, we were "treated" (see what I did there?) to some pretty wild weather. In 2014, gale force winds gusting up to 60mph churned up BIG waves along the southern shores of Lake Michigan. And in 2019, nearly 3.5" of snow fell across the city - the biggest snowfall Chicago ever recorded on Halloween. Here are a few of my favorite photos from those days. #ILwx #ChicagoWX

I've lived in Chicago since 2007 and had *never* been to the @themagmile Lights Festival - @amyulo and I were always out of town this weekend celebrating early Thanksgiving with her side of the family. But this year Amy arranged an opportunity to shoot the parade from the route itself and then get an elevated view for the post-parade fireworks show.

After we exited the parade we went up to the 19th floor of @401nmichigan to capture the fireworks over the river with @lhchicago in the background. We used suction cups to hang a huge black fleece drape from the window so we could shoot through them glare free - a standard lens skirt didn't work in this application. All in all we're pretty happy with what we caught considering this was our first experience. Here are a couple of my favorite fireworks frames. The first and third are single exposures, while the middle frame is a 5-frame composite. 

I'll share a few parade shots to my story in the next day or so. Cheers to the holidays kicking-off! // #ChiArchitecture #magmilightsfest #itstartshere

Earth’s axial tilt is the reason for the seasons — Happy Winter Solstice to all who celebrate! Evergreen trees and their branches have a rich history going back to cultures like the Romans, Celts, Egyptians, and Vikings, symbolizing life’s persistence during dark and cold winters. 

The tradition of decorating trees started in 16th-century Germany, but the Christmas tree as we know it gained popularity in the mid-1840s, thanks to Queen Victoria and Prince Albert displaying them in their home. 

Cheers to the beginning of winter, but also longer days!

Over winter break, we had some fun filming and photographing this polished pyrite sphere using the #iphone15promax’s macro function. 

@amyulo gifted it to me as an early Christmas present from @village_and_vessel in Oak Park. Pyrite, an iron sulfide, displays shimmering crystals with a pale brass-yellow color, often earning it the well-known nickname - fool’s gold.

While it’s challenging to predict the snow totals for Friday’s storm - especially downtown thanks to warmer-than-normal lake waters - what is clear is that a deep freeze will be “hot” on this storm’s heels. 

The 10-day forecast predicts temperatures below 32°F until around Tuesday, January 22nd!  We’re in for a 10-ish day stretch of literal freezing temperatures. Although the weather will be brutal, particularly on Monday and Tuesday, there is potential for some beautiful and otherworldly scenes along the river and lakefront. Remember to #LayerUp if you venture out. // #ILwx #ChicagoWX

Every time temperatures drop below zero I crave a trip to the lakefront.
